00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:03.920
&gt;&gt; You mentioned that you've
gotten his military records.

00:35:03.920 --> 00:35:09.240
Did you go to other areas, other
libraries, or other institutions

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:12.090
to get more information
on your father?

00:35:12.090 --> 00:35:16.040
&gt;&gt; Cecilia Garcia-Akers: Well,
fortunately, fortunately, in 1990,

00:35:16.040 --> 00:35:20.630
he donated, my father
donated his entire collection

00:35:20.630 --> 00:35:23.330
to Texas A&amp;M Corpus Christi.

00:35:23.330 --> 00:35:27.520
So, they are in possession of,
you're not going to believe this,

00:35:27.520 --> 00:35:31.820
7000 photographs, and
over the length

00:35:31.820 --> 00:35:34.210
of a football field in documents.

00:35:34.210 --> 00:35:39.080
Now, he never threw away anything,
so as you can tell, but he would,

00:35:39.080 --> 00:35:41.050
what he would do every
morning, he would go

00:35:41.050 --> 00:35:42.860
and buy the Corpus
Christi Colored Times.

00:35:42.860 --> 00:35:45.890
He would buy like three
copies, and he would go and mark

00:35:45.890 --> 00:35:48.730
with a felt pen each article.

00:35:48.730 --> 00:35:53.390
Like he would say, file under
John Kennedy, or Lyndon Johnson,

00:35:53.390 --> 00:35:57.520
or Civil Rights, whatever that
article was he was interested in,

00:35:57.520 --> 00:36:01.060
and they would make
scrapbooks and so on.

00:36:01.060 --> 00:36:06.130
And you're talking about, yeah,
I think at one time he had wanted

00:36:06.130 --> 00:36:10.510 position:56%
to take care of this cataloguing it,

00:36:10.510 --> 00:36:14.190
but it's so massive
that he had to donate.

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:16.940
He didn't have the
resources, not only financial,

00:36:16.940 --> 00:36:22.030
but you have to have certain people
to be able to handle these old --

00:36:22.030 --> 00:36:27.250
I mean, these pictures that
I've donated are from the 1940s,

00:36:27.250 --> 00:36:30.310
and my mother, fortunately,
saved everything also.

00:36:30.310 --> 00:36:35.980
So, we have hundreds of photographs
at the house, when they were dating

00:36:35.980 --> 00:36:40.010
and when they got married, just
beautiful photographs that,

00:36:40.010 --> 00:36:42.310
you know, I intend to
do something with later.

00:36:42.310 --> 00:36:45.750
But fortunately, I was
able to go to A &amp; M

00:36:45.750 --> 00:36:50.920 position:56%
and pull all his military
documents and look at them that way,

00:36:50.920 --> 00:36:54.810
and separation papers
were very interesting,

00:36:54.810 --> 00:36:58.970
and that's where I found
his US citizenship papers.

00:36:58.970 --> 00:37:02.600
And I knew that he had
fibbed about that one year,

00:37:02.600 --> 00:37:06.120
but because the citizenship papers
were different form the Army

00:37:06.120 --> 00:37:09.670
Separation papers, the
dates and where he was born.

00:37:09.670 --> 00:37:13.400
So, thank, you know, thank God,

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:17.200
I had those resources
to research his life.

00:37:17.200 --> 00:37:19.180
I didn't do a whole lot.

00:37:19.180 --> 00:37:21.820
I mean, I did all his
military records

00:37:21.820 --> 00:37:28.540
and also the discrimination
case, CCISD, in Corpus Christi

00:37:28.540 --> 00:37:30.320
because that was a
big struggle for him.

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:32.470
It took about eight
years, so there was lots

00:37:32.470 --> 00:37:34.040
and lots of information on that.

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:37.600
So, that's, and that's how I
did it, and that's what he did.

00:37:37.600 --> 00:37:39.710
He just clipped articles, and he,

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:43.240
lots of times he had young children
work in his office, young teenagers

00:37:43.240 --> 00:37:45.780
that were getting through high
school, and he would put them

00:37:45.780 --> 00:37:48.310
to work, and he'd come
in with the newspapers,

00:37:48.310 --> 00:37:51.480
and they would start cutting them
out and putting them in scrapbooks.

00:37:51.480 --> 00:37:55.240
There were no computers
back then either, you know.

00:37:55.240 --> 00:37:56.540
Yes?

00:37:56.540 --> 00:38:00.230
&gt;&gt; There was no congratulations for
producing the manuscript and all

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:01.800
that research in six months.

00:38:01.800 --> 00:38:03.100
&gt;&gt; Cecilia Garcia-Akers: Yeah.

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:04.400
&gt;&gt; Printing process.

00:38:04.400 --> 00:38:05.700
&gt;&gt; Cecilia Garcia-Akers: It was.

00:38:05.700 --> 00:38:07.000
It was. I don't know how we did it,

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:09.030
but thank goodness my
husband was here to help me.

00:38:09.030 --> 00:38:12.970
&gt;&gt; And I was just wondering if you
had any advice for somebody else

00:38:12.970 --> 00:38:18.040
who might want to write a book
about a family member, a memoir,

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:21.060
if you have any advice at
all about that process?

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:22.510
&gt;&gt; Cecilia Garcia-Akers: Well,
I, you know, you have to,

00:38:22.510 --> 00:38:27.650
it has to come from your heart, you
know, and what I did was, you know,

00:38:27.650 --> 00:38:31.550
my business is I'm in the car
driving around to patient's homes

00:38:31.550 --> 00:38:34.980
about ten hours a day, so I
had a lot of time to think.

00:38:34.980 --> 00:38:37.400
Turn the radio off.

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:40.680
But on Sundays, I would just start
writing, one chapter at a time,

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:43.850
write, write, write, you know,
whatever I could remember.

00:38:43.850 --> 00:38:47.080
And then, my dear husband would
type it up for me, and so a couple

00:38:47.080 --> 00:38:50.760
of days later I would go and
correct it or add things to it.

00:38:50.760 --> 00:38:56.060 position:56%
But in the car, I would write little
notes or what I wanted to change

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:58.310
or ask myself a question,
what about this?

00:38:58.310 --> 00:39:02.560
You know, memories started coming
back to me as I was writing.

00:39:02.560 --> 00:39:06.870
I think the hardest part of
writing a book is the organization,

00:39:06.870 --> 00:39:09.430
how you want to organize
the chapters.

00:39:09.430 --> 00:39:14.170
And of course, the History Press
had their own manuscript guidelines

00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:19.950
like how many spaces and how
many words and, you know,

00:39:19.950 --> 00:39:25.310
they were very strict about that,
and it had to be on a certain file,

00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:28.950
and we had to, you know, send
everything in, and photographs had

00:39:28.950 --> 00:39:33.360
to be a certain way, and they had
to be 6 and 1/2 inches in length,

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:39.140
and they, you know, they
wouldn't take any small ones.

00:39:39.140 --> 00:39:42.710
So, a lot of them I wanted to use,
a lot of the photographs I wanted

00:39:42.710 --> 00:39:45.490
to use, they wouldn't accept
them because they were too small.

00:39:45.490 --> 00:39:47.320
Some of them were too grainy.

00:39:47.320 --> 00:39:50.520
So, I think it's just, you know,
if you get more than six months,

00:39:50.520 --> 00:39:54.190
I think you'd probably do a good
job, but they were in a hurry

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:59.500
to get this book published,
and it was published April 4th.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:03.610
So, I think it just has to come
from here, to answer your question,

00:40:03.610 --> 00:40:07.730
and to organize your thoughts.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:09.030
Yes?

00:40:09.030 --> 00:40:11.730
&gt;&gt; I'm wondering if you
could tell us a little bit

00:40:11.730 --> 00:40:16.950
about his relationship
with LBJ, and did he know

00:40:16.950 --> 00:40:21.380
about [inaudible] veterans because
I believe they were both involved

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:26.100
in the Civil Rights Movement?

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:29.740
&gt;&gt; Cecilia Garcia-Akers: Lyndon
Johnson, you know, they started,

00:40:29.740 --> 00:40:33.610
of course, my father was a lifelong
Democrat, you know, he just,

00:40:33.610 --> 00:40:34.910
that's just the way he was,

00:40:34.910 --> 00:40:40.410
and he supported every Democratic
candidate that ran for President.

00:40:40.410 --> 00:40:42.920
Lyndon was, of course, from Texas,

00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:45.950
and they became close during
the Felix Longoria Affair

00:40:45.950 --> 00:40:47.690
because he was the only
one that would respond

00:40:47.690 --> 00:40:50.200
to my father's telegram
about getting some help.

00:40:50.200 --> 00:40:54.140
And he told my father that he
has, he cannot control what goes

00:40:54.140 --> 00:40:58.090
on in a private funeral
home but that he was going

00:40:58.090 --> 00:41:02.670
to have Felix buried in Arlington,
if his widow would accept it.

00:41:02.670 --> 00:41:06.280
So, that's how they
developed a relationship.

00:41:06.280 --> 00:41:12.160 position:56%
He became close to him, of course,
after John Kennedy was assassinated.

00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:16.530
He was going to the
White House all the time.

00:41:16.530 --> 00:41:21.170
He was, as we say today, in
Lyndon Johnson's face, you know,

00:41:21.170 --> 00:41:28.450
about certain things, like Civil
Rights, and they became very close,

00:41:28.450 --> 00:41:30.290
and my father was not
shy about telling him,

00:41:30.290 --> 00:41:31.950
"You're doing a terrible job."

00:41:31.950 --> 00:41:36.220
I mean, they had terrible fights,
but they respected each other,

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:39.280
and Johnson finally came around.

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:44.880
You've seen that famous speech that
he gave on the Congressional floor

00:41:44.880 --> 00:41:49.650
about his first job was a
school teacher in Kutula, Texas.

00:41:49.650 --> 00:41:51.730
You've seen that, haven't you?

00:41:51.730 --> 00:41:57.880
And then he says that, he says that
he saw the sadness and the hunger

00:41:57.880 --> 00:42:00.640
in his students' eyes every
day as they showed up.

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:04.980
And he would spend his own money to
help give these children breakfast

00:42:04.980 --> 00:42:07.850
and take care of them, and
he said, "I never thought

00:42:07.850 --> 00:42:13.230
that I would one day have the
chance to help those children

00:42:13.230 --> 00:42:14.880
as President of the United States."

00:42:14.880 --> 00:42:16.640
They were from Kutula, Texas.

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:20.370
And I think my father had
a big influence on him,

00:42:20.370 --> 00:42:25.420
and they had high respect for each
other, but my father never shied

00:42:25.420 --> 00:42:28.660
from telling him off,
you know, he never did.

00:42:28.660 --> 00:42:29.960
He never did.

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:32.520
And Martin Luther King, a lot
of people ask me about that,

00:42:32.520 --> 00:42:36.650
and I just think that they
never really crossed paths,

00:42:36.650 --> 00:42:40.570
and a month before Dr. King was
assassinated there was a telegram

00:42:40.570 --> 00:42:43.970
that he sent my father telling
him, "I know that you're, you know,

00:42:43.970 --> 00:42:47.230 position:56%
involved in Civil Rights," and he
wanted to set up a meeting with him.

00:42:47.230 --> 00:42:50.400
It was a month before the
assassination, so they never did,

00:42:50.400 --> 00:42:52.000
they never did have that meeting.

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:55.240
I think my father followed
his career

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:57.670
and followed what he was doing,
but you know my father was

00:42:57.670 --> 00:43:02.150
in a different direction as far as
the veterans and Mexican Americans

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:03.700
and Hispanic Civil Rights.

00:43:03.700 --> 00:43:05.510
So, I don't think they
really crossed paths.

